    {
      "id": "MMD-008",
      "type": "mental-model",
      "label": "Second-Order Effects",
      "status": "active",
      "properties": {
        "entity_id": "MMD-008",
        "entity_type": "mental-model",
        "title": "Second-Order Effects",
        "subtype": "second-order-effects",
        "status": "active",
        "description": "Evaluate the downstream consequences of decisions beyond the immediate, obvious results. First-order thinking asks: \"What will happen?\" Second-order thinking asks: \"And then what?\" Failing to anticipate second-order effects leads to unintended consequences and policy resistance.\n",
        "core_question": "What are the downstream consequences of this decision, and what happens next?",
        "application_protocol": "1. Identify the direct, first-order outcome of the decision.\n2. For that outcome, ask: \"And then what? What does this trigger?\"\n3. Map out the secondary and tertiary consequences (branching paths).\n4. Look for feedback loops (positive or negative reinforcement).\n5. Pay special attention to delayed reactions or systemic reactions (e.g., competitor response).\n6. Assess whether the first-order benefit is worth the second-order cost.\n",
        "failure_modes": "Can lead to analysis paralysis. Downstream consequences become increasingly speculative and harder to predict. May cause over-cautiousness.\n",
        "complementary_models": [
          "MMD-001",
          "MMD-007"
        ],
