    {
      "id": "MMD-006",
      "type": "mental-model",
      "label": "Marketplaces",
      "status": "active",
      "properties": {
        "entity_id": "MMD-006",
        "entity_type": "mental-model",
        "title": "Marketplaces",
        "subtype": "marketplaces",
        "status": "active",
        "description": "Multi-sided platform dynamics: a business that creates value by connecting two or more distinct user groups who benefit from interacting with each other. Marketplaces have unique economics \u2014 they must solve the chicken-and-egg problem, manage cross-side network effects, and balance liquidity across both sides.\n",
        "core_question": "Are both sides better off? And does adding one side make the other side more valuable?",
        "application_protocol": "1. Identify all sides of the marketplace (typically buyers and sellers)\n2. Define what value each side gets from the marketplace\n3. Map cross-side network effects: does more buyers \u2192 more value for sellers? (and vice versa?)\n4. Identify which side is harder to acquire (constrained supply or constrained demand?)\n5. Determine take rate and economics (what % of GMV can you extract without disintermediating?)\n6. Identify disintermediation risk (when do buyers and sellers transact directly?)\n7. Map the chicken-and-egg bootstrapping strategy\n",
        "failure_modes": "Overestimates cross-side network effects in thin or fragmented markets. Underestimates disintermediation risk once relationships are established. Fails to account for one side gaining market power and renegotiating take rates.\n",
        "complementary_models": [
