    {
      "id": "MMD-007",
      "type": "mental-model",
      "label": "Optionality",
      "status": "active",
      "properties": {
        "entity_id": "MMD-007",
        "entity_type": "mental-model",
        "title": "Optionality",
        "subtype": "optionality",
        "status": "active",
        "description": "Preserve the right to make future choices. Actions and investments that keep options open have asymmetric value: their upside is uncapped, their downside is limited. Sacrificing optionality for short-term certainty is a common strategic mistake. In uncertainty, optionality is a form of capital.\n",
        "core_question": "Does this decision preserve, create, or destroy future options?",
        "application_protocol": "1. Identify what options this decision creates (new paths opened)\n2. Identify what options this decision forecloses (paths permanently closed)\n3. Estimate the value of the foreclosed options (option value, not expected value)\n4. Compare: is the certain gain worth the lost optionality?\n5. Search for ways to achieve the same goal while preserving more optionality\n6. Flag irreversible decisions for higher scrutiny (see reversibility field in Decision nodes)\n7. When uncertain, prefer the option that creates more future options\n",
        "failure_modes": "Overvaluing optionality can lead to indecision \u2014 the \"option value trap.\" Some decisions require commitment to capture full value (network effects require scale). Optionality preservation can be used as rationalization for avoiding hard decisions.\n",
        "complementary_models": [
          "MMD-001",
          "MMD-008"
        ],
