      "id": "MMD-004",
      "type": "mental-model",
      "label": "Switching Costs",
      "status": "active",
      "properties": {
        "entity_id": "MMD-004",
        "entity_type": "mental-model",
        "title": "Switching Costs",
        "subtype": "switching-costs",
        "status": "active",
        "description": "The barriers \u2014 financial, operational, psychological, or technical \u2014 that prevent customers from switching to a competitor. High switching costs create defensibility and pricing power. Low switching costs create commoditization risk.\n",
        "core_question": "What makes it painful to stop using this product and start using a competitor's?",
        "application_protocol": "1. Enumerate all switching costs for the customer\n2. Classify: financial (contracts, sunk costs), operational (data migration, retraining),\n   psychological (brand loyalty, familiarity), technical (integration lock-in)\n3. Estimate switching cost in dollars and hours\n4. Compare to competitor pricing advantage needed to overcome the cost\n5. Identify which switching costs you control and can increase\n6. Identify which are eroding and require reinforcement\n",
        "failure_modes": "Switching costs can erode as technology lowers migration barriers. Artificially high switching costs (dark patterns) damage brand trust long-term. Competitors can intentionally reduce your switching costs (free migration tools).\n",
        "complementary_models": [
          "MMD-003",
